Ah, great catch — this is a really common point of confusion, so let me untangle it clearly. 🙂

Redis has TWO totally separate jobs in this project. You've mixed them up because they use the same Redis:

Job 1 — The Messenger (broker): carries background tasks. When you click "Refresh," fetch_weather.delay() drops a job into Redis, and the worker picks it up. ✅ This you've been using since the Celery lessons.

Job 2 — The Cache: stores the answer to an expensive question so you don't recompute it every time. ❌ This you have NOT used yet.

---
Now, "didn't we do cache at the very start?" — here's the subtlety:

At the start, you wrote the config in settings.py (the CACHES = {...} block). But that's just setup — like saving a phone number in your contacts. You've never actually called it.

Think of it this way:

┌───────────────────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────┐
│                What we did                │            What it is             │
├───────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────┤
│ CACHES = {...} in settings                │ ☎️ Saved the number (config)      │
├───────────────────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────┤
│ cache.get(...) / cache.set(...) in a view │ 📞 Actually calling it (using it) │
└───────────────────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────┘

We've never written a single cache.get or cache.set. So the cache is configured but sitting completely idle. No page has ever cached anything.

