Here's a story you'll feel. 🙂

---
The busy receptionist.

Imagine a receptionist at a big office front desk. All day, visitors walk up and ask the same question:

▎ "What's on the lunch menu today?"

The menu is pinned up in the kitchen at the far end of the building. So the first time someone asks, she gets up, walks all the way to the kitchen, reads the menu, walks back, and tells them.

Now the 10th person asks the same thing. Does she walk to the kitchen again? The 50th? The 100th? That's absurd — she'd spend her whole day walking.

So a smart receptionist does this: the first time, she walks to the kitchen, reads the menu, and writes it on a sticky note stuck to her desk. Every visitor after that, she just glances at the note and answers instantly — no walking.

When the kitchen changes the menu, she tears off the old note and writes a fresh one.

---
Now map it to your dashboard:

┌───────────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│        Receptionist story         │             Your dashboard              │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Walking to the far kitchen (slow) │ Querying PostgreSQL (slow-ish)          │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ The lunch question, asked 100×    │ 100 users loading the dashboard         │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Sticky note on the desk (instant) │ Redis cache                             │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Glancing at the note              │ cache.get(...)                          │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Writing the note the first time   │ cache.set(...)                          │
├───────────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Tearing it off when menu changes  │ cache.delete(...) when new data arrives │
└───────────────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────────────────────┘

---
The reason we need it:

Right now, every single page load walks to the database. One user, fine. But 100 users hitting the page = 100 trips to the kitchen — the database gets hammered doing the exact same query over and over, and every visitor waits.

The cache says: compute the answer once, keep it on a sticky note, serve everyone from the note. The database relaxes, and the page flies.

⚠️ And the one danger — the whole reason we'll be careful: if the menu changes but you forget to tear off the old note, you serve people stale info. That's why every time new weather arrives, we must cache.delete(). Stale cache is the classic silent bug.

